-- Regression: REG-02 crash-canary for IRON_HIR_EXPR_PARALLEL_FOR.
--
-- **Motivating Incident.** Phase 37-02's collect_mono_enums_node
-- walker crashed on if/elif/else lowering because of a locally-
-- shadowed struct typedef. The same class of walker-incompleteness
-- can re-emerge for any expression kind the lower_expr switch
-- handles. Parallel-for dispatch produces a worker-pool task
-- expression whose body runs N times across the thread pool, and
-- walker cases that fail to recurse into the body silently drop the
-- per-iteration work from the lowered LIR. Because reading outer
-- variables inside parallel bodies is not yet supported, the canary
-- output is produced from a separate sequential aggregate computed
-- after the parallel-for returns -- that keeps the fixture
-- deterministic while still exercising the dispatch path.
--
-- **Layout Diagram.** Iron_ParallelFor carries
--   { span, kind, iterator_var, bound_expr, body, parallel_flag }
-- Walker cases that fail to recurse into `body` produce an empty
-- parallel loop (no-op) with no compile error. Walker cases that
-- mis-read `bound_expr` dispatch zero iterations or an out-of-range
-- count, both of which fall through silently.
--
-- **Fix Summary.** Phase 67-08 added this fixture as a REG-02 crash
-- canary. Copies the dispatch pattern from tests/integration/
-- parallel_for_capture.iron and tests/integration/hir_parallel_for.iron
-- (body does its own arithmetic without reading outer state; main
-- then runs a sequential aggregate for the deterministic print).
-- CI integration: runs in both Debug and Release via Phase 66-04's
-- build-and-test-release job.
--
-- **Severity.** H (regression potential) -- parallel-for is the
-- THARD-07 dispatch mechanism and a walker regression produces
-- silently-wrong output under normal execution.

func main() {
  for i in 50 parallel {
    var work = i * i
    work = work + 1
  }
  var total = 0
  for i in range(10) {
    total = total + (i * i)
  }
  println("sum: {total}")
}
